title: Library Contract Request: ProQuest Ebook Central at Austin Community College

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Library Contract Request: ProQuest Ebook Central at Austin Community College
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with ProQuest (Clarivate) relating to the licensing of Ebook Central;

2) All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and

3) All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to the contractual relations with ProQuest (Clarivate) for Ebook Central licensing. 

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of Ebook Central.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ellen Dubinsky

communications.subject: ORR 3151 Confirmation Receipt of Your Request for Information
communications.communication:
Please accept this as confirmation of your request for information as
allowable by the Office of the Attorney General of the State of Texas.  We
will contact you if we require clarification from you before fulfilling
your request. Should ACC need additional time to comply with your request,
you will receive notice of the reason for the delay and an approximate date
the information shall become available.
Pursuant to Section 552.261 of the Texas Public Information Act, the
district will charge 10 cents per page for copies or charge for time and
labor for programming or gathering the information that you've requested at
$15 per hour.  If your request exceeds $40, you will be provided a detailed
cost estimate.  You must respond in writing within 10 days after the
estimate is sent that you will accept the costs, or that you desire any
stated alternative, or your request will be considered withdrawn. Payment
can be made online at ACC Marketplace after your estimate is provided.

If the estimated charge is more than $100.00, the College may ask for a
prepaid deposit before providing the information.

You may ask the College to determine whether providing the information
primarily benefits the general public, resulting in a waiver or reduction
of charges.

Your request has been logged and will be tracked as ORR 3151.

Please contact me if you have any questions about this information.

Thank you,


Dahlia Anzaldua-Torres
Office of College Relations & Marketing
austincc.edu
512-223-7595

ACC Highland Campus
6101 Highland Campus Drive
Austin, Texas 78752

title: Request for Body Cam Footage of Arrest and Interrogation

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Request for Body Cam Footage of Arrest and Interrogation
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Incident Details for Footage Retrieval:

Date: December 11, 2024
Location: Miami Beach, FL
Suspects: Alon Alexander, Oren Alexander
Incident Summary: The Alexander brothers were arrested by Miami Beach Police as part of a multi-state investigation into alleged sex trafficking and sexual assault. The bodycam footage reportedly captures their arrest and subsequent interrogations, with Oren Alexander being transported to a police vehicle before questioning began approximately 10 minutes later. A similar interrogation took place with Alon Alexander in a separate room. The total footage reportedly lasts nearly two hours.
I am requesting copies of all body-worn camera footage from officers who:

Participated in the arrests of Alon and Oren Alexander.
Transported the suspects.
Conducted or were present during their interrogations.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Harun

title: Cameron Oliver sheriff office- records request

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: Cameron Oliver sheriff office- records request
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Good Day. I hope you are doing well. 
I am requesting the following records from your agency.
 Can you please provide a list of deputies  currently employed by the sheriff office   by name and rank. Also by District. 
Drug crimes possession of all illegal drugs. 
I want a list of the suspects'  drugs charges and the deputy   who made the arrest. 
I want crime data on this crime from the years 2021-2025. 
Also, a list of the most frequent crimes your community faces. 

Let me know if you have any questions or concerns. 
I look forward to hearing from you. 
If possible please send all requested records by email. 
Thank you. 
Take care and be well. 

Best regards,
 Cameron Oliver 
904-489-9118
oliverkidsjax@gmail.com

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Cameron John Oliver

communications.subject: RE:  South Carolina Public Records Law Request: Cameron Oliver sheriff office- records request
communications.communication:
Good Morning, Cameron,

In response to your Freedom of Information Act request, we have attached the most current roster for the Charleston County Sheriff's Office.

As far as the other part of your request, that is not a record we keep in that way, and under the South Carolina FOIA law, we cannot "create" records to fulfill a request. I encourage you to use our Crime Map, which I have linked below. There, you will be able to narrow it down by the type of crime and set a time period, for example, from 2020 -2025, if that is what you are looking for.

LexisNexis® Community Crime Map<https://www.communitycrimemap.com/map>
LexisNexis® Community Crime Map<https://www.communitycrimemap.com/map>
Research events reported to local law enforcement agencies with the LexisNexis® Community Crime Map. Search for events by location, viewing results on the map, in a data grid or through analytics on the data for the location selected.
www.communitycrimemap.com
We will consider this request closed.

Best,


Alexis (Lexi) Douglas

Public Information Officer, Charleston County Sheriff's Office

3691 Leeds Avenue · North Charleston, SC 29405

ADouglas@CharlestonCounty.org

C: 843-666-1990 | O: 843-958-2114

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Jonathan Daria Arrest – March 29, 2025
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting all records related to the arrest of Jonathan Michael Daria on March 29, 2025, at approximately 7:14 PM, by the Lake County Sheriff’s Office in Paisley, Florida.

According to public records, Daria was arrested and charged with:

Domestic Battery by Strangulation – Florida Statute 784.041(2)(a), a third-degree felony

Specifically, I am seeking:

The complete arrest and incident reports, including officer narratives, witness/victim statements, and supplemental documentation

Any available body-worn camera (BWC) footage from responding deputies

911 call audio and transcripts

Any photos, video evidence, or CAD/dispatch records

Documentation related to injuries, medical response, or use of force

Due to the serious nature of the charge, this request is made in the interest of public oversight and law enforcement accountability in domestic violence investigations.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Thomas Jackson

title: Emails sent and received by Athletic Director Beth Goetz that contain one of four keywords

communications.subject: Iowa Open Records Law Request: Emails sent and received by Athletic Director Beth Goetz that contain one of four keywords
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Iowa Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

All emails sent and received by Athletic Director Beth Goetz from Jan. 1, 2024 through May 15, 2024 that contain any of the following four terms:

1. Larissa
2. Libby
3. Gymnastics
4. Education and Sports Law Group

I ask that the emails be retrieved via separate keyword searches.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Welsh

communications.subject: RE: [External] Iowa Open Records Law Request: Emails sent and received by Athletic Director Beth Goetz that contain one of four keywords
communications.communication:
Ben,

This is to confirm receipt of your request, copied below.

We will put together a time/cost estimate for searching for, retrieving, and reviewing responsive records, in accordance with our fee schedule<https://transparency.uiowa.edu/faqs/public-records-fee-schedule>. Please note that your keywords - in particular, "Gymnastics" - may produce a high volume of responsive records (including schedules, media releases, etc.), so the time to compile and review records could be substantial. If you would like to narrow the scope of your request, please let me know.

Please also note that records may be exempt from disclosure based on confidentiality exceptions under Iowa Code Chapter 22, including but not limited to, Iowa Code 22.7(11) (confidential personnel records).

Finally, your date range goes into the future (May 15). We don't process future requests for records that don't yet exist. We will retrieve responsive records up to the time your request was received.

Thanks,
Aubree


Aubree Johnson
Public Records Officer
The University of Iowa
351 Plaza Centre One
Iowa City, IA 52242
public-records@uiowa.edu<mailto:public-records@uiowa.edu>

NOTICE TO RECIPIENT: THIS MESSAGE AND ANY RESPONSE TO IT MAY CONSTITUTE A PUBLIC RECORD, AND THEREFORE, MAY BE AVAILABLE UPON REQUEST IN ACCORDANCE WITH IOWA PUBLIC RECORDS LAW, IOWA CODE CHAPTER 22.

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas SEA response
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA".

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the Texas Education Agency sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

title: Public Records Request – Francisco Sanchez-Alfaro DWI Arrest (March 2025)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Public Records Request – Francisco Sanchez-Alfaro DWI Arrest (March 2025)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting public records related to the arrest of Francisco Sanchez-Alfaro, an 18-year-old male who was arrested by the Dallas Police Department after crashing into a Dallas police sergeant’s vehicle while driving under the influence. The incident occurred on or around March 25, 2025, just before 3 a.m. at or near Cedar Springs Road and Manor Way, near Dallas Love Field Airport.

The subject, Francisco Sanchez-Alfaro, was reportedly intoxicated and driving a Chevy Camaro when he ran a red light and collided with a Dallas police vehicle during a routine patrol. The officer's car was forced off-road, and the Camaro hit a utility pole. Sanchez-Alfaro was arrested and booked into the Dallas County Jail without bond and placed on an immigration hold.

Please include the following records:

Body-worn camera footage from all officers involved in the incident

Dashcam footage from the patrol vehicle(s)

911 call recordings and dispatch (CAD) logs

Arrest report, incident report, and DWI affidavit

Mugshot (if publicly releasable)

Any internal review or supplemental records related to the use of force or crash

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Christopher Udeani

title: Significant Incident Report - Unreported Atlanta In-Custody Death

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Significant Incident Report - Unreported Atlanta In-Custody Death
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. CBP's Notification to CRCL re the Death of Narendra Kayastha
A notification by U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) to DHS-CRCL reporting the in-custody death of Narendra Kayastha, an 80 year-old Indian man who died around 7 pm on November 26, 2021, at 4945 Governors Drive in Forest Park, Georgia, while in CBP custody for an immigration inspection. 

CBP's Death notification policy required CBP's Office of Professional Responsibility to notify CRCL through the Privacy and Diversity Office. Page 5. https://www.cbp.gov/sites/default/files/assets/documents/2021-Sep/2021_notification-review-procedures-for-certain-deaths-and-deaths-in-custody%20%283%29.pdf. 

CBP's press website did not post notification of Kayastha's death to its public website, and has not acknowledged this death publicly. 

2. CBP's Significant Event Notification (SEN) or Significant Incident Report (SIR) re the Death of Narendra Kayastha
The CBP-Atlanta SEN or SIR for Mr. Kayastha's death. 

We respectfully request expedited processing of this request pursuant to 6 CFR 5.5(e), and make the following statements in support thereof under penalty of perjury pursuant to 28 USC 1746: 
1. Narendra Kayastha died in CBP custody during an inspection for immigration violations around 7pm on November 26, 2021 in Forest Park, Georgia. See: https://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/24413601/cbp-2023-083502_opr_recordpdf.pdf (row 5). 
2. Mr. Kayastha was witnessed going unresponsive and medical help was contacted, according to the Georgia Bureau of Investigation's autopsy report. See https://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/24674455/2021-1037549-0001.pdf (page 2). 
3. CBP did not release a public statement regarding Mr. Kayastha's in-custody death, as required by the agency's death notification policy. https://www.cbp.gov/sites/default/files/assets/documents/2021-Sep/2021_notification-review-procedures-for-certain-deaths-and-deaths-in-custody%20%283%29.pdf 
4. The public has no information regarding what prompted Mr. Kaystha to become unresponsive, how long it took to provide him medical care, or whether he received appropriate care once a provider was contacted. 
5. The address CBP recorded for Mr. Kayastha's death is not a hospital emergency department--it is an outpatient, walk-in clinic called Southside Medical Center. https://southsidemedical.net/forest-park/. 
6. There is an urgency to inform the public about this alleged federal government activity, and I am a journalist primarily engaged in the dissemination of information.  Specifically, the public has a right to know immediately how Mr. Kayastha died in government custody, why CBP failed to notify the press, and why he was not transported to a higher level care facility. 
7. The absence of a public statement by CBP regarding Mr. Kayastha's death reflects an apparent instance of noncompliance with CBP's death notification policy that was in effect at the time.  There is an urgent to need to inform the public regarding why and how this apparently noncompliant death response occurred.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

CBP-FO-2024-114173 

Dear Andrew Free: 
This notice acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) received on 5/24/2024.  Please use the following unique FOIA tracking number CBP-FO-2024-114173 to track the status of your request.  If you have not already done so, you must create a SecureRelease account. This is the only method available to check the status of your pending FOIA request. 

Provisions of the Act allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS FOIA regulations outlined on the DHS website, https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations. By submitting your request, you have agreed to pay up to $25.00 in applicable processing fees, if any fees associated with your request exceed this amount, CBP shall contact you. 
Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, CBP processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although CBP’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). 

CBP’s FOIA Division is working hard to reduce the amount of time necessary to respond to FOIA requests.  We truly appreciate your continued patience. 
For additional information please consult CBP FOIA website please click on FOIA Act Resources or visit http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia. 

Please note that this message has been sent from an unmonitored e-mail account. Any messages sent to this account will not be read. 
Sincerely, 

U.S. Customs and Border Protection

communications.subject: CBP FOIA - CBP-FO-2024-114173
communications.communication:
Andrew Free 
N/A 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR164180 
263 Huntington Ave 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

01/28/2025 

CBP-FO-2024-114173 

Dear Andrew Free: 

A search of CBP databases produced records responsive to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request CBP-FO-2024-114173, requesting records maintained by CBP. 

CBP has determined that the responsive records are partially releasable, pursuant to Title 5 U.S.C. § 552 and have applied the appropriate exemptions notated below: 

Exemption Summary: 
(b)(6) 
Pursuant to exemption  (b)(6), 0 pages have been withheld in full and 3 pages in part. 
Permits withholding of records and information about individuals when disclosure would be a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy. 
(b)(7)(C) 
Pursuant to exemption  (b)(7)(C), 0 pages have been withheld in full and 3 pages in part. 
Permits withholding of records when an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy could reasonably be expected. 
(b)(7)(E) 
Pursuant to exemption  (b)(7)(E), 0 pages have been withheld in full and 3 pages in part. 
Permits withholding of records when techniques and procedures for law enforcement investigations or process would be disclosed or provided such disclosure could reasonably be expected to risk circumvention of law. 

Pursuant to DHS Instruction 262-11-004, FOIA Officers at DHS have been instructed to withhold personally identifiable information (PII) and sensitive personally identifiable information (SPII) of DHS personnel unless a determination is made that the disclosure does not raise security or privacy concerns, or if those concerns are outweighed by any public interest in that information. This policy is available online. Under this policy, the names of senior leaders, spokespersons, and political appointees are generally releasable. With respect to this FOIA request, DHS may have applied FOIA Exemption 6 to protect PII of DHS employees, including names and contact information. To the extent that has DHS withheld employee PII within these records, it has been determined that the employee(s) has/have substantial and legitimate privacy interests and that these interests are not outweighed by any public interest in the operations of the Department. 

For your information, Congress excluded three discrete categories of law enforcement and national security records from the requirements of the FOIA. See 5 U.S.C. 552(c).  This response is limited to those records that are subject to the requirements of the FOIA. This is a standard notification that is given to all our requesters and should not be taken as an indication that excluded records do, or do not, exist. 

You may notice a recent date on the attached records. This is the date our processor queried the record in response to your FOIA request. For clarity, it is not the date the agency first created the record. 
The following item(s) also apply to your request: 

•	Approximately 0 pages were withheld in their entirety. 
•	Fees: In the processing of this FOIA request, no fees are being assessed. 
•	Other: 

This completes the CBP response to your request.  You may contact CBP's FOIA Public Liaison, Charlyse Hoskins, by sending an email via your SecureRelease account, mailing a letter to 1300 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW MS 1181, Washington DC, 20229 or by calling 202-325-0150. (If you need telecommunication relay service (TRS) assistance to communicate with the CBP FOIA Office and you are in the United States, please dial 711 to obtain TRS assistance and notify the Communications Assistant that you want to contact the CBP FOIA Office at the telephone number (202) 325-0150). The FOIA Public Liaison is able to assist in advising on the requirements for submitting a request, assist with narrowing the scope of a request, assist in reducing delays by advising the requester on the type of records to request, suggesting agency offices that may have responsive records and receive questions or concerns about the agency’s FOIA process. Please notate file number CBP-FO-2024-114173 on any future correspondence to CBP related to this request. 

If you are not satisfied with the response to this request, you have a right to appeal the final disposition.  Should you wish to do so, you must file your appeal within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS regulations at Title 6 C.F.R. §5.8.  Please include as much information as possible to help us understand the grounds for your appeal.  You should submit your appeal via your SecureRelease account . If you do not have computer access, you may send your appeal and a copy of this letter to:  FOIA Appeals, Policy and Litigation Branch, U.S. Customs and Border Protection, 90 K Street, NE, 10th Floor, Washington, DC 20229-1177.  Your envelope and letter should be marked "FOIA Appeal." Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia.  Additional information can be found at the following link https://www.cbp.gov/sites/default/files/assets/documents/2019-Dec/definitions-exemptions-foia_0.pdf. 

Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769. Please note that contacting the CBP FOIA Public Liaison or OGIS does not stop the 90-day appeal clock and is not a substitute for filing an administrative appeal. 

Please note that this message has been sent from an unmonitored e-mail account. Any messages sent to this account will not be read. 
Sincerely, 
U.S. Customs and Border Protection

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: New Jersey DOC transgender policies
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All department policy and guidance documents regarding transgender inmates, including but not limited to gender-affirming medical care, housing and treatment by staff. I also request records of any proposed and/or enacted changes to said policies made on or after Nov. 6, 2024 until date of search, if such documents exist.

I request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

communications.subject: OPRA 23418
communications.communication:
Dear  Requester,

The requested record is attached.  Rutgers University provides medical care.  You may wish to file an OPRA with that agency for medical care policies.

You have a right to challenge the decision by the Department of Corrections.  At your option, you may either institute a proceeding in the Superior Court of New Jersey or file a complaint in writing with the Government Records Council (GRC).  You may contact the GRC by toll-free telephone at 866-850-0511, by mail at P.O. Box 819, Trenton, NJ 08625, by e-mail at Government.Records@dca.nj.gov<mailto:Government.Records@dca.nj.gov> or at their web site at www.state.nj.us/grc<http://www.state.nj.us/grc>.  The Council can also answer other questions about the law.

Thank you,
John Falvey
NJDOC Records Custodian

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

Renee

As also discussed, we will require additional time to provide the remainder of the records.  We plan to provide additional documents on or before February 1, 2024.  Thank you again for your continued patience regarding this matter.
Regards,
Renee

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Illinois SEA response
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA".

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the Illinois Department of Education sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

title: America First Legal FOIA re: Visas

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: America First Legal FOIA re: Visas
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

(1) All records produced in response to the January 2, 2024, FOIA request from America First Legal (issued by Will Scolinos);

(2) Any correspondence sent to or from the requester with respect to that FOIA request.

REQUEST FOR EXPEDITED PROCESSING:

I request that this request be expedited under 6 CFR § 5.5(e)(1)(ii) for the following reasons. Please note that the underlying request was processed on an expedited basis.

1. I certify the following to be true and correct: My organization is primarily engaged in disseminating information. The Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression (FIRE) maintains a news website at https://thefire.org/news, through which its staff members regularly publish news stories and editorial content concerning the activities of governments, government officials, and other persons or organizations of public concern. I am a staff member of FIRE. I frequently write about matters involving the First Amendment and free expression, including on FIRE's website. See, e.g., https://www.thefire.org/news-archive?author=303. A substantial component of my duties as a staff member of FIRE is to obtain information through public records requests, including through the Freedom of Information Act, which I or my colleagues then share through FIRE's website and social media channels. I also publish news and other information of public concern via "X" (https://x.com/adamsteinbaugh) and "Bluesky" (https://bsky.app/profile/adamsteinbaugh.bsky.social).

2. The requested information concerns an actual or alleged government activity, namely the Department's production of records in response to a FOIA request.

communications.subject: Department of Homeland Security FOIA 2025-HQFO-03937 Acknowledgment
communications.communication:
04/23/2025 

SENT VIA E-MAIL TO:  185340-09920453@requests.muckrock.com 

Adam Steinbaugh 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR185340 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

Re:  2025-HQFO-03937 

Dear Requester: 

This letter acknowledges receipt of your 4/21/2025, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to the Department of Homeland Security (DHS), for: 
(1) All records produced in response to the January 2, 2024, FOIA request from America First Legal (issued by Will Scolinos); 
(2) Any correspondence sent to or from the requester with respect to that FOIA request. 

This office received your request on 4/21/2025. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, the Department processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although DHS’ goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS FOIA regulations as they apply to non-commercial requesters.  As a non-commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free, as are the first two hours of search time, after which you will pay the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00.  This office will contact you before accruing any further fees. 

We have queried the appropriate component(s) of DHS for responsive records.  If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability.  Please be assured that one of the analysts in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible.  We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 

Your request has been assigned reference number 2025-HQFO-03937.  Please refer to this identifier in any future correspondence. 

If you have any questions, or would like to discuss this matter, please feel free to contact this office at 1-866-431-0486 or 202-343-1743.

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Division of Community Care (DCC) Roster
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

A complete and current roster of all former and current employees of the Division of Community Care (DCC), including for each employee:

Full name
Age
Gender
Race
Job title
Department or division
Work email address (if available)
Date of hire (if available and non-exempt)
Date of termination (if relevant)

If any of the above fields are exempt from disclosure, please redact only the exempt information and release the remainder of the records in accordance with the partial disclosure provisions of applicable public records law. I am not requesting any personally identifiable information that is protected by law, such as Social Security numbers or personal contact information.

I would prefer to receive this information in electronic format (e.g., CSV, Excel, or PDF) if available.

If there are any fees for searching or copying the records, please inform me before processing the request. I also request a waiver of fees as the information is being sought for research and public interest purposes, not for commercial use.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Filed Requests

All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA".

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the Pennsylvania Department of Education sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

Andrew Free

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2021-HQFO-00312
communications.communication:
I have provided you a link to the specific source of records I seek. I am not required by ICE’s regulations to identify a contract number. Nor will I. You, on the other hand, are required to conduct a good-faith, timely search with the strong presumption in favor of disclosure wherever ambiguity exists. The timing and content of your follow-up is evidence you are violating these statutory and regulatory obligations. Consequently, if you fail to conduct a search based on my failure to identify a contract number, I intend to seek referral of this matter to the Office of Special Counsel and report your office’s illegality to relevant oversight committees in Congress. 

Please cease your office’s ongoing lawbreaking. Conduct an adequate search and release all non-exempt portions of responsive records without further delay. 

Thank you,

Andrew

communications.subject: Your City of Los Angeles public records request #25-5306 has been closed.
communications.communication:
City of Los Angeles ************************************************************************ Record request #25-5306 has been closed. The closure reason supplied was: Dear Requester,   We have received your request for officer deployment records related to the LASAN CARE+ and RESET operations.   Your request was made under the California Public Records Act (the Act). The Department is cognizant of its responsibilities under the Act. It recognizes the statutory scheme was enacted to maximize citizen access to the workings of government. The Act does not mandate disclosure of all documents within the government’s possession. Rather, by specific exemption and reference to other statutes, the Act recognizes that there are boundaries where the public’s right to access must be balanced against such weighty considerations as the right of privacy, a right of constitutional dimension under California Constitution, Article 1, Section 1. The law also exempts from disclosure records that are privileged or confidential or otherwise exempt under either express provisions of the Act or pursuant to applicable federal or state law, per California Government Code Sections 7927.200; 7927.700; 7923.600-7923.625; 7927.705; and 7922.000. In regard to Deployment records, specifically names and number of officers involved, to the extent the record exists, the Department has a strong interest in maintaining the confidentiality of records that consist of or contain detailed tactical, operational, deployment information, and analysis of potential threats. Disclosure of this information to the public has the potential to enable would-be perpetrators to discern areas of vulnerability and the intelligence assessments, evade security procedures, thereby endangering the operation of the Department and the safety of its officers and the public in the event of similar law enforcement initiatives. Therefore, these records are exempt from disclosure. In regard to hourly costs, please refer to the City Controller's website at the following link: Payroll Explorer   If you have any questions, please respond to this email.   Respectfully,   LAPD Public Records & Subpoena Response Section, CPRA Unit ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at City of Los Angeles.

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello, 

I am requesting records and data related to Senate Bill 674. The law requires certifying agencies that receive certification requests must annually report to the Legislature the number of victims that requested certifications from the particular agency, the number of certifications signed, and the number of certifications denied. The certifications are for U and T Visas. 

I am requesting 
- The annual reports sent to the legislature as legally required since 2018. 
- Department U visa certification policy and protocols since 2024
- Bulletins, emails, memos, directives, or any communications from DHS and/or United States Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) regarding SB674 and Form I-914s. Search January 2025 to today's date. 
- Any memos, bulletins, directives, or formal communications regarding U and T Visas. Search from 2020 to today's date. 

Thank you!

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

communications.subject: Colorado Open Records Act Request: CORA Surety Bond / Liability Insurance Request
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am filing a request under the Freedom of Information Act, The Sunshine Act 5 U.S.C. § 552b, and The Colorado Open Record Act (CORA) C.R.S. § 24-72-201.

NOTICE TO PRINCIPAL IS NOTICE TO AGENT

I request an electronic copy of the following documents:

As Per HB 13-1072:

 * Individual, Schedule, or Blanket Corporate Surety Bond (if applicable)  - CO Rev Stat § 20-1-101
 * Public Official Surety Bond (if applicable) - CO Rev Stat § 22-32-104(1)4b
* Surety Liability Insurance Policy (if applicable). 
* Acceptable Security. CO Rev Stat § 20-1-101
* Criminal Insurance Policy if applicable. 
* Power of Attorney Surety Bond Company
* Blanket Power of Attorney Blanket Surety Bond from Surety Bond Company if applicable
* Good Faith Insurance Policy if Applicable
* Errors & Omissions (E&O, a Surety Liability Insurance policy, and the Duty of Care policy if applicable
* Certificate of Liability
* Faithful Performance Bond
* Fidelity Bond
* Public Employee Dishonesty Policy
* Statutory Bond
* Deputy of Care policy
* Risk Management Policy
* Oath of Office
* A photocopy of the following documents if applicable:
      ACORD 125
      ACORD 126
      ACORD 127
      ACORD 128
The documents should indicate the policy number and the insured amount of the policy.

I am requesting the above documents for the following individuals:

Michael Hancock - Mayor of Denver
Molly Duplechian - Executive Director, Office of Excise and License
Dominic Vianna - Deputy Director, Office of Excise and License
Brian Snow - Lead Investigator, Office of Excise and License

If you are not the custodian of records for this request, please forward this letter to the appropriate person or let me know who to contact for these records. I request a waiver of all fees for searching or copying these records in that the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public's understanding of short term rental license enforcement abuse in Denver, Colorado.

Please supply this record to me via email within a reasonable time (3 working days) or less pursuant to C.R.S. § 24-72-203(3)(b). Also pursuant to the same section, records that are readily available should be provided right away. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is NOT being made for commercial purposes.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

pooanon

communications.subject: Re: Denver CORA Request
communications.communication:
Muckrock.com recipient:

I write in response to your attached request. Department of Finance has conducted a good faith search for the records you requested and the responsive record located is attached. We have attached our "Government Crime Insurance" policy, which is what we believe you mean when you say "criminal" insurance. This policy has been renewed with the same conditions as of 5/1/25, but we do not yet have the new policy in hand. Also below is an email sent for the same request dated March 11, 2022.

The Denver Clerk and Recorder would most likely be the custodian of any additional records within the scope of your request, and you may submit requests to that office if you wish to do so. You can find contact information for them at the following link:

https://www.denvergov.org/Government/Agencies-Departments-Offices/Agencies-Departments-Offices-Directory/Clerk-and-Recorder/find-records/CORA

This response is governed by the Colorado Open Records Act and applies only to records in the custody of the Department of Finance. Thank you for your inquiry. Please let us know if you have any questions.

files.source: Denver Department Of Finance, Denver, CO

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Washington SEA reponse
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA".

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the Washington Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. Ileana Garnand: Thank you for contacting the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI). You requested: [External]Washington Public Records Act Request: Washington SEA reponse 

May 1, 2025 
To Whom It May Concern: 
Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: 
All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA". 
I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the Washington Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications. 
I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage. 
In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 
Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 
Sincerely, 
Ileana Garnand

Walla Walla County ************************************************************************ Your record request #25-302 has been submitted successfully. This letter serves as Walla Walla County’s initial five-day letter, pursuant to RCW 42.56.520, to your public records request. After your request is reviewed for content and we determine the department or office in which your request refers to, the County will provide an estimate to provide an initial installment of responsive records. After locating responsive records, the County will determine whether any of the responsive documents are subject to applicable exemptions under the Public Records Act, and to notify any third parties affected by the request. If third party notification is required, twenty (20) business days will be allowed for a response by the third party to those records which specifically pertain to them. As records are reviewed, they may be released on an installment basis. Additionally, the Washington Public Records Act (RCW 42.56.120) and Walla Walla County Resolution 23-201 now allow the County to charge for provision of electronic records. communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Massachusetts DOC transgender policies
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

All department policy and guidance documents regarding transgender inmates, including but not limited to gender-affirming medical care, housing and treatment by staff. I also request records of any proposed and/or enacted changes to said policies made on or after Nov. 6, 2024 until date of search, if such documents exist.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fchicago-public-schools-3121%252Fcps-principal-personnel-files-2025-185490%252F%253F&url_auth_token=AAATZ164Jy60iQjs6iHTUOyYGcc%3A1u7m0R%3A5DCsNoeFcz62G5ZU5RgofLYAhatxlnTyhqFvWdxH3IM RESPONSE: Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Please note that certain private information (personal descriptions, employee ID numbers, college transcripts, social security numbers, citizenship status, signatures, personal addresses/phone numbers, medical information, names of victims, etc.) was redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7. Specifically, section 7(1)(b) which exempts certain private information as defined by section 2(c-5) and section 7(1)(c) which exempts personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subject of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs any legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a) exempts “ information specifically prohibited from disclosure by federal or State Law … ” (5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a)) Specifically, 105 ILCS 5/10-21.9 (b) states that “ any information concerning the record of convictions obtained by the president of the school board or the regional superintendent shall be confidential and may only be transmitted to the superintendent of the school district or his designee, the appropriate regional superintendent if the check was requested by the school district, the presidents of the appropriate school boards if the check was requested from the Department of State Police by the regional superintendent, the State Superintendent of Education, the State Teacher Certification Board, any other person necessary to the decision of hiring the applicant for employment, or for clarification purposes the Department of State Police or Statewide Sex Offender Database, or both.” 
Portions of this request that include personnel evaluations are redacted entirely in accordance with section 7(1)(a) of FOIA (5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a)) which exempts from public release information specifically prohibited from disclosure by federal or State law or rules and regulations implementing federal or State law and also in accordance with section 7.5(q) of the FOIA (5 ILCS 140/7.5(q)) which exempts from public release information prohibited from being disclosed by the Personnel Records Review Act [820 ILCS 40/0.01 et seq.] Student information has been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). Identities of complainants have been redacted pursuant to section 7(d)(iv) of the FOIA which exempts confidential information furnished only by the confidential source, or persons who file complaints with or provide information to administrative, investigative, law enforcement, or penal agencies. You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

    I request that your agency conduct a full CRS search, as well as a cross
    reference search, to retrieve records related to this prominent American.
    
    The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and
    this request is not being made for commercial purposes.
    
    In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me
    of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the
    request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM
    if not.
    
    Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look
    forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days,
    as the statute requires.
    
    Sincerely,
    
    Ben Welsh
    
    Upload documents directly:
    https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Ffederal-bureau-of-investigation-10%252Ffbi-files-colin-powell-120336%252F%253Femail%253Defoia%252540subscriptions.fbi.gov&url_auth_token=AAAj2DhBAMB3M81TmD2Oe8C8-1M%3A1mdOd1%3AnGAn9WNk_v9hI3J4XK7jWMXXxkw

Supporting documentation **

Please be advised that efoia@subscriptions.fbi.gov is a no-reply email
address. Questions regarding your FOIA request may be directed to
foipaquestions@fbi.gov. If you have received a FOIPA request number, please
include this in all correspondence concerning your request. Please note eFOIPA
requests are processed in the order that they are received. If you have not
received a FOIPA request number, your request is in the process of being
opened at which time it will be assigned a FOIPA request number and
correspondence will be forthcoming.

** 

Upon receipt of your FOIPA request number, you may check the status of your
FOIPA request on the FBI’s electronic FOIA Library (The Vault) on the FBI’s
public website, http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on the ‘Check Status of Your
FOI/PA Request tool’ link. Status updates are performed on a weekly basis. If
you receive a comment that your FOIPA request number was not located in the
database, please check back at a later date.

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1507448-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 111 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 895 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,929 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Leonard Zeskind
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning or describing Leonard Zeskind, who tracked right-wing hate groups. He was born in 1950 and died on April 15, 2025. His death was widely covered in the press: 

https://www.nytimes.com/2025/04/24/us/politics/leonard-zeskind-dead.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. This is also to include any responsive records held in offsite locations, such as the Alexandria Records Center. Please include both investigatory and non-investigatory records in your search.

If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

I am a member of the news media and request classification as such. I have previously written about the government and its activities, and am currently a reporter of The Boston Globe.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alexa Gagosz

title: FBI support for 2023 FX miniseries "Class of '09"

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI support for 2023 FX miniseries "Class of '09"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documents pertaining to FBI support for or collaboration with the production of the 2023 FX TV miniseries "Class of '09." Such documents may include, but are not limited to, script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of the FBI and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "Class of '09," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication. I request a search of all locations where such documents might be located, including but not limited to the entertainment liaison offices and communications HQ or similar offices.

Attached is a document, released to me by the FBI in response to a previous FOIA request, confirming that the FBI supported the production of "Class of '09."

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

Andrew Free

Thanks very much for following up. 

If the decentralization of the FOIA offices means there won’t be DHS FOIA records of those trainings and they’ll be with ICE FOIA instead, it makes sense to do an intra-agency referral for the ICE records. We consent to that. 

If the other offices’ trainings referenced on page 10 won’t be likely to be stored by ICE FOIA, or if DHS FOIA has them, maybe you can retain and task only that portion of the request? I’d consent to that as well.

Best regards,

Andrew

February 10, 2022 Andrew Free MuckRock News DEPT MR 122446 411A Highland Ave Somerville, Massachusetts 02144-2516 RE:     ICE FOIA Case Number 2022-ICFO-07344  Dear  Free: This acknowledges receipt of your January 13, 2022, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for all DHS FOIA policy and training materials referenced on Page 10 of the DHS Chief Privacy Officer's 2018 Chief FOIA Officer Report: https://www.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/publications/2018%20Chief%20FOIA%20Officer%20Report.pdf, as well as all subsequent versions of FOIA policy and training materials provided to DHS FOIA personnel and DHS agency components’ FOIA personnel AFTER 2018 DHS Chief Privacy Officer’s FOIA report and BEFORE December 21, 2021.  Your request was received in this office on January 13, 2022. PLEASENOTE: Requesters seekingresponsive records from the U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) areencouraged to create a DHS FOIA Public Access Link (PAL) accountat: . Creating a PALaccount will allow you to directly submit your FOIA request to ICE and trackthe status of your request. In PAL, you can view your prior PAL submissions,sent correspondences, and responsive records. Although PAL is preferred, ICEFOIA will continue to accept FOIA requests via email at (https://foiarequest.dhs.gov/) https://foiarequest.dhs.gov or via regularmail at U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement, Freedom ofInformation Act Office, 500 12 ICE-FOIA@ice.dhs.gov th St. SW, STOP 5009, Washington,DC 20536-5009. Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10- day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you care to narrow the scope of your request, please contact our office. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 
Your request has been assigned reference number 2022-ICFO-07344. Please refer to this identifier in any future correspondence. To check the status of an ICE FOIA/PA request, please visit . Please note that to check the status of a request, you must enter the 2022-ICFO-07344 tracking number. If you need any further assistance or would like to discuss any aspect of your request, please contact the FOIA office. You may send an e-mail to ice-foia@ice.dhs.gov, call toll free (866) 633-1182, or you may contact our FOIA Public Liaison, Marcus Francis, in the same manner. Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation. If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974. You may contact OGIS as follows: Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769.
