communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2022-ICFO-07344
communications.communication:
Ms. Cisneros: 

I am appealing: 

(1) DHS’s failure to make a timely determination on all three requests.
The agency has NEVER made the legally required determination. See CREW v. FEC (DC Cir 2013) for a summary of your unmet obligations in making a determination. 

(2) DHS’s January 2022 referral / transfer decision to ICE. 
We separately sought the same records from ICE. What we wanted in making this request was insight into what supervision—or lack thereof—the DHS Chief FOIA/PA Officer engages in when it comes to this serially deficient and unlawful component’s conduct. DHS has violated FOIA by failing to ensure ICE responds to this referral in a timely manner. 

(3) DHS’s failure to timely provide an estimated date of completion.
The agency has never even attempted to comply with this statutory obligation 

(4) DHS’s failure to make responsive records promptly available. 
A  year and a half response period is unreasonable and violates 5 USC 552(a)(3)(A). See Owen v. ICE (CD Cal). 

Please adjudicate this appeal. 

Thank you.

communications.subject: ICE FOIA Case Number 2022-ICFO-07344
communications.communication:
Andrew Free 
MuckRock News DEPT MR 122446 
Somerville, Massachusetts 02144-2516 

RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2022-ICFO-07344 
 
Dear Requester: 

This letter is the final response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 1/13/2022.  You have requested all DHS FOIA policy and training materials referenced on Page 10 of the DHS Chief Privacy Officer's 2018 Chief FOIA Officer Report: https://www.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/publications/2018 Chief FOIA Officer Report.pdf, as well as all subsequent versions of FOIA policy and training materials provided to DHS FOIA personnel and DHS agency components’ FOIA personnel AFTER 2018 DHS Chief Privacy Officer’s FOIA report and BEFORE December 21, 2021. 

ICE has considered your request under both the FOIA, 5 U.S.C. § 552, and the Privacy Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552a.  Information about an individual that is maintained in a Privacy Act system of records may be accessed by that individual unless the agency has exempted the system of records from the access provisions of the Privacy Act. 

ICE has conducted a search of the ICE Office of Regulatory Affairs and Policy (ORAP) for records responsive to your request and no records responsive to your request were found. 

For your information, Congress excluded three discrete categories of law enforcement and national security records from the requirements of the FOIA.  See 5 U.S.C. § 552(c) (2006 & Supp. IV (2010).  This response is limited to those records that are subject to the requirements of the FOIA.  This is a standard notification that is given to all our requesters and should not be taken as an indication that excluded records do, or do not, exist. 

While an adequate search was conducted, you have the right to appeal this determination that no records exist within the above mentioned ICE office(s).  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of the original response letter, within 90 days of the date of the letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.8.  You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

Provisions of FOIA allow DHS to charge for processing fees, up to $25, unless you seek a waiver of fees.  In this instance, because the cost is below the $25 minimum, there is no charge. 

If you have any questions please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St., SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009 and refer to your tracking number. Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 
Sincerely, 

ICE FOIA Office 
Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: CPS: Incident Reports, August 2024
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Supply records sufficient to show a listing of incident reports (ICT Record List) from August 1, 2024 through August 31, 2024 for all CPS schools.

This request is made on behalf of The FOIA Bakery. Because this request is in the public interest for Illinois nonprofit The FOIA Bakery’s work to advocate for public education, please waive any fees in accordance with 5 ILCS § 140/6(c). Feel free to contact me with any questions, or if clarification is needed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Miriam Bhimani

Miriam Bhimani 

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fchicago-public-schools-3121%252Fcps-incident-reports-august-2024-185486%252F%253F&url_auth_token=AAATZ164Jy60iQjs6iHTUOyYGcc%3A1u7lyi%3A1AMyyo2dH74yq7kH4IHRpgVqe5Dnyq1usdsdn_9plAM RESPONSE: Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Please be advised that certain event reasons have been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c) exempts personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy... “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs any legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

title: Senate Study of the CIA's Detention and Interrogation Program [CIA]

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act.  I hereby request the following records:

A document entitled "The Central Intelligence Agency's Response to The
Senate Select Committee on Intelligence Study of the CIA's Detention
and Interrogation Program", or similar, as well as any documents which reference this document, or which went into the compilation of this document, or which were produced as a result of this document's production and circulation.

The existence of this document was revealed on the White House's 'Flickr' stream at this location: http://farm3.staticflickr.com/2871/9095100853_299fc8ac77_o.jpg - showing the document in the possession of CIA Director John Brennan.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that fees cannot be waived, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rich Jones

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Alabama Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Any open zoning, building, or fire code violations currently on record; the date of the last fire code compliance inspection; and the certificates of occupancy for Brook Highland Place Apartments, 1 Meadow Drive, Birmingham, AL 35242

This request is being made for a commercial purpose

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

André Natta, a citizen of Alabama, in coordination with Lindsey McQuiddy.

title: FOIA Navy military record Peter F Irish  USN ret Vietnam

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA Navy military record Peter F Irish  USN ret Vietnam
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The Official Military Personnel File (OMPF) for Peter F Irish including all Fitness Report and Counseling forms NAVPERS Form 1610/2, Enlisted performance evaluation reports NAVPERS Form 1616-1, the Background Summary (NAVPERS Form 1640/32), Most recent Cumulative Record of Training (NAVPERS Form 5300/16), history of assignments NAVPERS form 601-5 and/or NAVPERS form 1070/605, Navy Training History NAVPERS form 601-4, all military awards and full citations, military education/training courses and Form DD-214. 
Also request medal full Citations for all awards if possible. Mr Peter Irish was a decorated Navy veteran of the Vietnam War.
If necessary please redact any sensitive information protected in accordance with the Privacy Act of 1974.

VETERAN INFORMATION

Name of veteran: Peter F Irish
Branch of service: United States Navy
SSN/SN:  B12  38  06
Rank: navy petty officer 2nd class
Dates of military service: Approximately 1964 - 1975
Date of birth: Approximately 1944-1950

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest . The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Donavan Turner

title: FOIA Navy military record Everett E. Barrett  USN, ret  Vietnam

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA Navy military record Everett E. Barrett  USN, ret  Vietnam
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The Official Military Personnel File (OMPF) for Everett E. Barrett including all Fitness Report and Counseling forms NAVPERS Form 1610/2, all Enlisted performance evaluation reports NAVPERS Form 1616-1, forms NAVPERS Form 1610/1, the Background Summary (NAVPERS Form 1640/32), Navy Training History NAVPERS form 601-4, Most recent Cumulative Record of Training (NAVPERS Form 5300/16), history of assignments NAVPERS form 601-5 and/or NAVPERS form 1070/605, final active duty photograph, all military awards and full citations, military education/training courses and Form DD-214. 
Also request Bronze Star Medal and Navy Commendation medal full Citations. Mr BARRETT was a decorated veteran of the Vietnam War.
If necessary please redact any sensitive information protected in accordance with the Privacy Act of 1974.

VETERAN INFORMATION
Name of veteran: Everett E. BARRETT
Branch of service: United States Navy
SSN/SN: 379  35  52
Rank: Master Chief Petty Officer E9
Dates of military service: Approximately 1948 - 1975
Date of birth: Approximately 1928
date of death: 	January 14, 2010


I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest . The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press .

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Donavan Turner

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Grappler incident reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All incident reports and dash cam video since January 1, 2023 documenting department personnel using a Grappler Police Bumper system.

2) Department policies and instructions governing the use of the Grappler Police Bumper system.

If you have any questions about this request, please do not hesitate to ask. If you would like to set up a time to discuss this request over the phone, please email me at tips@toddfeathers.com.

I am requesting these records as a journalist in order to write articles in the public interest about the operations of a government agency and not for any commercial purpose.

In the event that you determine certain records or portions of records are exempt from disclosure, I ask that you provide a detailed explanation of the records or portions of records being withheld and the statutory exemptions under which they are being withheld.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

communications.subject: Your City of Albuquerque public records request #24-13306 has been submitted.
communications.communication:
City of Albuquerque ************************************************************************ Your record request #24-13306 has been submitted successfully. Greetings: We have received your request for public records and will begin processing your request. This correspondence is intended to acknowledge your request and alert you that it may take up to fifteen days to process your request. NMSA 1978 14-2-8(D). We will be in contact with you as we process your request if we need additional information or if it appears that your request is excessively burdensome and broad. Additionally, please let us know if you have or later acquire documents relating to your request and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Please be advised, if you are requesting lapel and/or 911 audio from the Albuquerque Police Department (APD), your request may take a significant amount of time to review and provide the records. In lieu of the 911 audio, my office can provide the Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD). The CAD provides information of when the call was received, when and what officers were dispatched, and a description of what happens throughout the incident. In addition, please keep in mind a 5 minute lapel video can take up to 20 minutes to review depending on the type of redactions that are necessary to complete. We will be in contact to discuss ways to narrow your request but you are also welcome to contact us to discuss narrowing options. If you have or later acquire documents relating to your request, please let us know and upload the records into NextRequest. Such additional information has proven to be a useful resource in identifying, locating, and producing additional records. Please do not hesitate to contact us if you would like to know the status of your request, and please communicate all questions and status updates via NextRequest. The Office of the City Clerk reserves the right to charge an advance/deposit fee for materials related to records production and data extraction.  You may access your request by signing into your NextRequest profile at the following website:  https://nextrequest.cabq.gov/users/sign_in  Sincerely, Ethan Watson City Clerk ************************************************************************ Reply to this email or sign in to contact City of Albuquerque.

communications.subject: [Invoice Created] City of Albuquerque public records request #24-13306
communications.communication:
City of Albuquerque ************************************************************************ An invoice has been created for record request #24-13306. Hello,   This communication will acknowledge completion/or partial completion of your public records request dated November 12, 2024. Please be aware: protected personal identifier information contained in the requested records was redacted pursuant to NMSA 1978, § 14-2-1.1. I have redacted portion(s) of the records because they are exempt from disclosure under IPRA, NMSA 1978, Section 14-2-1(A) (medical records); Section 14-6-1(A) (medical records); Section 14-2-1(L) (as otherwise provided by law, including NMRA Rule 11-504 (physician-patient and psychotherapist-patient privilege)). See generally 45 C.F.R. §§ 160, 164 (HIPAA). I also redacted certain information which could reveal the identities of undercover police officers or informants. This information is exempt from the Inspection of Public Records Act. See NMSA 1978, § 14-2-1.2(A)(7) (confidential sources, methods or information). If made public, the redacted information would seriously interfere with the effectiveness of criminal investigations and prosecutions, and endanger undercover police officers or informants. Responsive Records: * Reports (Invoiced) The responsive records are available for purchase, please see the invoice that was released to you for the price and mailing address; once we receive payment, we will mail the records to you; you may also come into our office to pay for and pick up the records with exact cash or check/money order. Please call our front desk to schedule an inspection 924-3650. Thank you for your patience. communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Herb Powless FBI FOIA (Federal Bureau of Investigation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documents and files, including letters, memos, emails and all communications pertaining to the co-founder of the American Indian Movement Edward Joseph Benton, also known as "Eddie Benton-Benai" (born March 4, 1931 - died November 30, 2020), an obituary of whom was published in the Guardian on December 2, 2020. A copy of his obituary is attached to this request as a PDF, and it may also be found at https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/dec/03/eddie-benton-banai-co-founder-of-american-indian-movement-dies-aged-89

I would also like to request a search of all available cross-index files for mentions of Edward Joseph Benton, also known as "Eddie Benton-Benai," in other documents, to be included with this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Nicholas Estes

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1499610-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 152 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 922 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,964 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Kendrick D. Gillum Evidence
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arkansas Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1.	All evidence collected in relations to the case of Kendrick D. Gillum, Antonio Williams, and Demarco Wilson’s murder of Charles Newsome (hereinafter "the case of Charles Newsome's murder").
2.	All records cataloging the evidence in this case, and identifying the location(s) of the evidence at the time of such cataloging.
3.	All records, if any, referencing the “loss” of any of the evidence in the case of Charles Newsome’s murder.
4.	All records, if any, referencing the “misplacement” of any of the evidence in the case of Charles Newsome’s murder.
5.	All records, if any, referencing to the signing out of any of the evidence in the case of Charles Newsome’s murder, and any returning of evidence that had been signed out. 
6.	All records identifying any policies or procedures to be followed by the WMPD in preserving evidence seized in criminal cases. 
7.	All records evidencing any communications by one or more of the West Memphis Police Department police officers or any other members of the WMPD and any third-parties concerning the evidence in the case of Charles Newsome’s murder from February 1, 1997 to date.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sonny Albarado, a citizen of Arkansas, in coordination with Marc Howard.

RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of 3/12/2025., Reference # R010030-031225. Dear Martin  Brooks, The Calcasieu Parish Sheriff's Office received a public information request from you on 3/12/2025. Your request mentioned: We are needing a valid state issued photo I.D. from the person requesting the records to verify that they are of or over the age of 18.  Louisiana law requires the requester to be at least 18 years of age to make a public records request. La. R.S. 44:31. The only information that we will need from the I.D. is the requester's full name, photo, and date of birth.  All other information may be redacted from the I.D. if you wish to do so. I will not be able to mail your request until I receive an ID. To upload a photo of your I.D. you will need to go to the My Records Center, click on , click on the View My Requests button, click on the Details button, and then click the New Message button.  Once you've uploaded your I.D., then click the Attach Send Button If you have any questions or need additional information, please feel free to respond to this email. Sincerely, Christina O'Quinn Legal Clerk Legal Department

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records: 

All emails sent to or received from @kiro7.com email addresses since November 1, 2024, including attachments and associated metadata. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Rose Terse

In accordance with RCW 42.56.520, we are notifying you that additional time is required to process your request due to our current volume of public record requests and our need to prioritize other essential government functions, the size and scope of the responsive records, and/or legal review. 
We may process this request in installments (RCW 42.56.120 / WAC 44-14-07006).  The Records Division expects to provide the first installment or all responsive records on or before May 9th, 2025.  You will be notified of any fees due once the installment is complete. 
Please be advised, an agency may require a deposit in an amount not to exceed ten percent of the estimated cost of providing copies for a request.  If you have multiple active requests with our agency, we will queue your requests separately ( in most cases finishing the first one received before starting on the next, etc.), in order to also provide records to other requesters. Cordially,
